definition.value: Permission to do something.

A collective generic term that refers here to a wide variety of dependencies, areas of special sovereignty, uninhabited islands, and other entities in addition to the traditional countries or independent states.
Anything that contributes causally to a result.
The act of entering into or through something.
A measurement of degree, speed, or frequency relative to time.
The process or technique of obtaining a representative sample.
A condition or state at a particular time.
The act of going to see some person or place or thing; it can cover a short or long period but refers to a non-permanent arrangement.
A lack of occurrence or performance.
A healing process and/or an outcome implying relative health. The term is typically used in the context of direct and indirect effects of sickness or injury.
Any act or phenomena, or behavior, constituting a reply or reaction of a living organism or its part to some foregoing stimulus or agent.
A state of ill health caused by medical treatment, usually due to mistakes made in treatment.

Any part of, or extract from, the female hemp plant Cannabis sativa. Marijuana contains cannabinoids, substances with hallucinogenic, psychoactive, and addictive properties. This agent has potential use for treating cancer pain and cachexia.

The dried leaves and flowering tops of the Cannabis sativa plant, or an extract from the plant. Marijuana is being studied in the treatment of nausea and vomiting caused by chemotherapy or opiate drugs, such as morphine sulfate. Marijuana is also being studied in the treatment of pain.
An inflammatory disease affecting the brain parenchyma.
A non-neoplastic or neoplastic disorder that affects the gonads.
A non-neoplastic or neoplastic disorder that affects the larynx.
Infection due to organisms from the genus Mycobacteria.
Bleeding originating from the vagina.
Congenital or acquired deficiency of one of the coagulation factors. It results in bleeding.
Any of various syndromes primarily affecting the endocrinological system of the body.

A non-neoplastic or neoplastic disorder that affects the anatomic structures of the head and neck region. This category includes inflammatory disorders, benign neoplasms, precancerous conditions, and malignant neoplasms.
A non-neoplastic or neoplastic disorder that affects the anatomic structures of the neck region. This category includes disorders of the pharynx, larynx, thyroid gland, and parathyroid gland.
A person 13 to 18 years of age.
Administration of a drug into a location within the body; this can be achieved either through an established access or via a needle.
A surgeon who performs organ transplants.

A prosthesis used to change the size, shape, and contour of a person's breast. In reconstructive plastic surgery, breast implants can be placed to restore a natural looking breast mound for post–mastectomy breast reconstruction patients or to correct congenital defects and deformities of the chest wall. They are also used cosmetically to enhance or enlarge the appearance of the breast through breast augmentation surgery.
A change resulting in something that is different from the original.
The act or process of modifying something.

The theoretical totality of characteristics of reproductive structure, functions, phenotype, and genotype, differentiating the male from the female organism. In practice, many cases occur where a majority of characteristics occur aligning with "maleness" or "femaleness", with a minority not fitting those expectations. "Sex" therefore is often not specific enough of a term to be useful. Consider using something like "gonadal sex" or "chromosomal sex" instead.

"Sex" is an extremely complicated term with many different meanings, both historical and contemporarily, as well as colloquially. It should be avoided, and more specific terms should be used in its place (such as "chromosomal sex" or "hormonal sex").
A non-metastasizing neoplasm that arises from the ovary. Representative examples include serous cystadenoma, mucinous cystadenoma, clear cell adenofibroma, benign Brenner tumor, thecoma, and fibroma.
A neoplasm of the breast.
A non-neoplastic or neoplastic disorder affecting the heart or the vessels (arteries, veins and lymph vessels).
Someone who takes part in an activity.
A non-neoplastic or neoplastic disorder that affects the endocrine system.
A poorly circumscribed neoplasm arising from the soft tissues. It is characterized by the presence of spindle-shaped fibroblasts and an infiltrative growth pattern.
A benign, borderline, or malignant neoplasm that affects the müllerian reproductive system.

A benign, borderline, or malignant neoplasm that affects the wolffian reproductive system. Representative examples include benign prostate phyllodes tumor, benign testicular Sertoli cell tumor, prostatic intraepithelial neoplasia, prostate carcinoma, testicular seminoma, and testicular embryonal carcinoma.
A deficiency of a blood coagulation factor characterized by the tendency to hemorrhage. Hemophilia is typically a hereditary deficiency but, rarely, may be acquired.
A genetic problem caused by one or more abnormalities formed in the genome.
An infection caused by a fungus.

Fibromatosis arising from the soft tissues of the penis. It is characterized by the presence of spindle-shaped fibroblasts, and an infiltrative growth pattern. It causes the penis to bend when it becomes erect.

A benign, borderline, or malignant neoplasm that affects the prostate gland. Representative examples include benign prostate phyllodes tumor, prostatic intraepithelial neoplasia, prostate carcinoma, and prostate sarcoma.
A non-neoplastic or neoplastic disorder that affects the urinary system.

A benign or malignant neoplasm that affects the uterine corpus or the cervix. Representative examples of benign neoplasms include leiomyoma, adenomyoma, and endocervical polyp. Representative examples of malignant neoplasms include endometrial carcinoma, carcinosarcoma, and cervical carcinoma.
An infection caused by a virus.
A pathologic process in the larynx that affects the production of speech.
An infection that is caused by any of various species of Chlamydia.
A disorder that results from a chromosomal abnormality.
A finding in which there is a subnormal amount of an enzyme. Enzymes are proteins that are necessary in certain catabolic processes.
A non-neoplastic or neoplastic disorder affecting the arteries, veins, or lymphatic vessels.
A congenital or acquired hyperplasia of the cells of the adrenal cortex or medulla.
